{"parentUuid":"cab466ba-0d82-489d-98f4-3b2f2f7086e0","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/ryan/formal-conjectures","sessionId":"ff14e81a-a848-4da2-834b-1987dfb608f5","version":"2.1.71","gitBranch":"ai-erdos-7","agentId":"a8ab707bc0b1915e5","slug":"velvet-waddling-dahl","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01TButURcsVECgiyfUBMpAZW","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/-\n     2→Copyright 2026 The Formal Conjectures Authors.\n     3→\n     4→Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the \"License\");\n     5→you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.\n     6→You may obtain a copy of the License at\n     7→\n     8→    https://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n     9→\n    10→Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software\n    11→distributed under the License is distributed on an \"AS IS\" BASIS,\n    12→WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.\n    13→See the License for the specific language governing permissions and\n    14→limitations under the License.\n    15→-/\n    16→\n    17→import FormalConjectures.Util.ProblemImports\n    18→\n    19→/-!\n    20→# Erdős Problem 594\n    21→\n    22→*Reference:* [erdosproblems.com/594](https://www.erdosproblems.com/594)\n    23→\n    24→A problem of Erdős and Hajnal: does every graph with chromatic number\n    25→$\\geq \\aleph_1$ contain all sufficiently large odd cycles? Proved by\n    26→Erdős, Hajnal, and Shelah [EHS74].\n    27→\n    28→[ErHa66] Erdős, P. and Hajnal, A., *On chromatic number of graphs and\n    29→set-systems*, Acta Math. Acad. Sci. Hung. **17** (1966), 61–99.\n    30→\n    31→[Er69b] Erdős, P., *Problems and results in combinatorial analysis and\n    32→graph theory*, Proof Techniques in Graph Theory (1969), 27–35.\n    33→\n    34→[EHS74] Erdős, P., Hajnal, A., and Shelah, S., *On some general properties\n    35→of chromatic numbers*, Topics in Topology, Colloq. Math. Soc. Janos Bolyai\n    36→**8** (1974), 243–255.\n    37→-/\n    38→\n    39→open SimpleGraph Cardinal\n    40→\n    41→namespace Erdos594\n    42→\n    43→/-- A graph has uncountable chromatic number: it cannot be properly colored\n    44→with countably many colors. -/\n    45→def HasUncountableChromaticNumber {V : Type*} (G : SimpleGraph V) : Prop :=\n    46→  ∀ (α : Type*) [Countable α], IsEmpty (G.Coloring α)\n    47→\n    48→/-- The cycle graph $C_m$ on $m$ vertices ($m \\geq 3$). Vertex $i$ is adjacent to vertex\n    49→$i + 1 \\pmod{m}$ and vertex $i - 1 \\pmod{m}$. -/\n    50→def cycleGraph (m : ℕ) (_ : m ≥ 3) : SimpleGraph (Fin m) where\n    51→  Adj i j := i ≠ j ∧ (j.val = (i.val + 1) % m ∨ i.val = (j.val + 1) % m)\n    52→  symm := fun _ _ ⟨hne, h⟩ => ⟨hne.symm, h.elim Or.inr Or.inl⟩\n    53→  loopless := fun _ h => h.1 rfl\n    54→\n    55→/-- $G$ contains a copy of $H$: there is an injective map preserving adjacency. -/\n    56→def ContainsCopy {V W : Type*}\n    57→    (G : SimpleGraph V) (H : SimpleGraph W) : Prop :=\n    58→  ∃ f : W → V, Function.Injective f ∧ ∀ u v, H.Adj u v → G.Adj (f u) (f v)\n    59→\n    60→/--\n    61→Erdős Problem 594 [ErHa66] [Er69b]:\n    62→\n    63→Every graph with uncountable chromatic number (i.e., chromatic number\n    64→$\\geq \\aleph_1$) contains all sufficiently large odd cycles. That is, there exists\n    65→$N_0$ such that for all odd $n \\geq N_0$ (with $n \\geq 3$), the graph contains $C_n$\n    66→as a subgraph.\n    67→\n    68→Proved by Erdős, Hajnal, and Shelah [EHS74].\n    69→-/\n    70→@[category research solved, AMS 5]\n    71→theorem erdos_594 : answer(True) ↔\n    72→    ∀ {V : Type*} (G : SimpleGraph V),\n    73→      HasUncountableChromaticNumber G →\n    74→      ∃ N₀ : ℕ, ∀ (n : ℕ) (hn : n ≥ 3), Odd n → n ≥ N₀ →\n    75→        ContainsCopy G (cycleGraph n hn) := by\n    76→  sorry\n    77→\n    78→end Erdos594\n    79→"}]},"uuid":"e6ed44ca-1c2a-4bef-b12e-ccd7acb930a6","timestamp":"2026-03-10T